message.content: Assume for contradiction that the set of all odd natural numbers is finite. Then there must be a largest odd natural number, say \( n \). Consider the number \( n+2 \). Since \( n \) is odd, \( n+2 \) is also odd. Moreover, \( n+2 > n \), which contradicts the assumption that \( n \) is the largest odd natural number. Therefore, the set of all odd natural numbers must be infinite.
